  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The proposed research is particularly relevant to the National ALS Registry and public
      environmental health issues because it addresses the potential environmental causes of
      sporadic ALS. The research will develop an ALS surveillance program in Ohio that can be
      compared with the national and State-Metro Surveillance Programs of the National ALS
      Registry, and novel methodologies to determine the role of the cyanobacterial toxin, BMAA,
      and other environmental toxicants as risk factors for ALS. This work will advance the mission
      of the CDC ATSDR National ALS Registry by offering data on ALS cases in Ohio that address
      public health concerns over the effects of chronic exposure to cyanobacterial blooms in Lake
      Erie.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
